A classic example of this is creating a function that generates binary trees. We can start with a basic tree structure and then enhance it with a function. We want a tree to generate a list of its leaf elements, where each leaf is a node value.

A good way to conceptualize this using recursion is that each function call represents doing work on one branch of the tree, and when you make a recursive call, you are asking the same function to do identical work on a different branch. To avoid doing the same work many times, we need a way to keep track of what's already been done. This is where we use a parameter, which we can call "seen," to keep track of all the leaf values. The most important part is understanding that the base case isn't for recursion, but for avoiding it in the first place. The ultimate purpose of using recursion is to make the function do as much work as possible in one go, not to let it take multiple calls.

Here is an example in JavaScript:
```javascript
const treeToList = (t, seen = []) => {
  if (t === null) {
    return seen; // No leaf (base case), so we just return seen.
  }
  if (t.left === null && t.right === null) {
    return [...seen, t.value]; // If t is a leaf, append it to seen.
  }
  return treeToList(t.left, [...seen, t.value]) 
   .concat(treeToList(t.right, seen));
};
```
This way, we only visit every non-leaf node once. If we just called `treeToList` recursively on `t.left` without checking if it was a leaf, we would have been doing duplicate work. The `seen` parameter allows us to keep the results and move on, creating a much more efficient algorithm than it would have been to have multiple, smaller recursive calls.
